annotations:
One minute i’ll be fucked
 And the next minute i’m fine

This could relate to BP, otherwise known as Bipolar Disorder. This can consist of wild mood swings and changes, and, as this line states, they’re “completely fucked, then they’re fine”. which can be a symptom of this disorder. Although there are many other things that this line could associate with, such as ADHD (Attention-Deficit Disorder), and other mental issues that are similar to these two. (Please note this could be a major stretch – it’s just my personal thoughts.)
Don’t romanticize my life

This can be taken in many different ways, although the way I took it in is how many insensitive people can glorify depression and mental health issues. There are many different types of people who do these kinds of things, some of the more common kinds being either someone who thinks it’s such a “cute” or “quirky” thing to have that they fake it themselves, or those who still thinks it’s just a “cute trait” and often obsessing over it or, in the context of this line, romanticizing it.

“Don’t romanticize my life” means that the narrator of this story deals with the issues that are commonly glorified in certain communities, supporting the theme of the song.

Theres something inside
 That fucking hurts me every time
 Ive tried every single
 Pill to help me chill
 And i’m not satisfied

“There’s something inside” can be taken in the way of poor mental health, the main theme of the song. Oftentimes people with mental health issues, more commonly depression and anxiety, often claim to have that voice inside their head that could be putting doubts into their thoughts, which can cause many people to have self-consciousness.
“I’ve tried every pill to help me chill and I’m not satisfied” can refer to anxiety medication, which a lot of people with depression and anxiety are given with their doctor’s permission. Sometimes these pills may have a huge impact on someone and improve their mental health, but it’s also common that it can have no effect on the person using it, no matter how long they’ve been taking it for.

description.plain:
awfultune gives some backstory to the 7th track on the “Peace and Quiet” album titled “Things That I Miss”

“this is the third part to the relationship in "Unkind Child” and “We Don’t Work Anymore”. a song about being hurt, a song about moving on, and then a song about reflecting. even though this was relationship was very toxic for me, i couldn’t help but write about the good times that we had. a reminder that when something turns sour, it doesn’t mean it wasn’t sweet once. the people we meet in life teach us a lesson, so never regret knowing a person. as much as it hurt, the good will bring happiness, the bad will teach you, and the best will give you memories.“ – awfultune

song.title: Maggot Belly

body.plain: “Maggot Belly” is a song told from the perspective of an abuse victim. The narrator illustrates the toxicity of their abusive partner by comparing the treatment they receive to that of insects.

annotations:
I didn’t think it would be that bad
 I saw the signs right in front of me and didn’t turn back
 I didn’t leave him
They thought that by returning to their partner, things would be different this time. They continued to ignore all the red flags from the previous time they were together.

I’ll beg my way ’til I get in
 ’Til I break my skin
 Lord, please forgive me for I have sinned

It is possible that this is relating back to the beginning of the song in which the narrator has had a confrontation with the abuser. The two may have had a falling out/break up. Despite that, however, the narrator decided to return to their partner once again. It is common for people in toxic relationships to return to their abusive partners for fear of being alone. The narrator may be aware deep down that what they are doing is wrong, hence they feel the need to repent.

I thought you wanted love like this
 And you said you wanted all of it

This relates back to the previous annotation with the maggots representing the narrator’s abuser. Despite their mistreatment, the narrator still believes this relationship to be that of love since the abuser told them “they wanted all of it”.

I’m gonna infest your brain
 Maggot belly, maggot belly, yeah
 Your bugs are eating me
Maggots are the larvae of flies that often eat off of dead animal carcasses. The maggots represent the abuser who “eats off” of the victim.

I’m gonna fuck up your picnic
 I’m gonna ruin your day
 You treat me just like an insect
 Crawling on your lace

The singer emphasizes the toxicity of this relationship by comparing it to the treatment of insects. Much like how picnic food becomes bad when infested by insects, the singer feels as though they themselves are the source of their partner’s issues.

I said I was difficult to love
 And you said that I make your head spin
 Well, guess I’m different
The narrator expresses that they feel as though they are underappreciated in the relationship, while their partner proves their point by stating that they make him feel frustrated.

Get out of my bed, put on your clothes, go back home
 You like to get drunk and treat me bad

The song starts with what we can assume to be a confrontation between the narrator and their partner. The narrator is insisting the abuser leave the house because of his abusive tendencies. We can assume that this other person is also an alcoholic.
